[2] UK (Wales)
Date: Thu 23 Feb 2012
Source: Caernarfon and Denbigh Herald [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.caernarfonherald.co.uk/caernarfon-county-news/local-caernarfon-news/2012/02/23/measles-outbreak-at-porthmadog-school-reaches-twelve-88817-30386065/

Measles outbreak at Porthmadog school reaches twelve
----------------------------------------------
The take-up of the MMR jab following an outbreak of measles in Porthmadog proved to be "very popular" yesterday (Wednesday). Twelve pupils have so far been clinically diagnosed with measles at Ysgol Eifionydd in Porthmadog, with headteacher Alwen Watkin stating she had never before seen a similar outbreak in her 20 year career.

Measles is a serious and highly contagious viral disease that can cause complications including pneumonia, meningitis and encephalitis. Mrs Watkin said: "This is the first time I've seen such an outbreak. The school was informed by a parent during last week's half term break that two children had been affected, and this number grew quickly during the course of the week."

Public Health Wales reported that the 12 pupils diagnosed with measles had either received no MMR vaccination or only one dose. The body's consultant in communicable disease control, Dr Chris Whiteside, called for parents in North Wales who have not arranged immunisation for their children to act immediately to get them vaccinated.

He said: "Measles is highly contagious and spreads very easily. We would therefore expect to see more cases. As long as there are children who have not had their two MMR vaccinations, there is the potential for people to become ill with measles. "There is then a danger for the disease to spread to unvaccinated friends, family or others who cannot be vaccinated due to existing health problems, and who are therefore highly vulnerable to measles infection."

Mrs Watkin added: "Other pupils are ill at the moment, but we can't yet confirm whether they have measles or not. "I know that many parents make a conscious decision not to immunise their children with the MMR jab. That's their choice, and we have to respect that, but if they do start showing symptoms, I'd ask them to stay away from the school, and to see their GP as soon as possible, as we don't want it to spread further around the school."

Ysgol Eifionydd held MMR and booster sessions for pupils who had not been vaccinated yesterday (Wednesday). Mrs Watkin said the sessions had proved "very popular".

(By Kevin White)

