[5] Afghanistan (WHO)
Date: Sat 25 Feb 2012
Source: SOSchildrensvillages [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.soschildrensvillages.ca/News/News/child-poverty-news/Pages/UN-Vaccinations-for-Children-Urgent-after-Afghan-Measles-Outbreak-141.aspx

Vaccinations for Children Urgent after Afghan Measles Outbreak
------------------------------------------------------
Severe weather and a low immunization cover combined with a measles outbreak has lead to a World Health Organization (WTO) call for all Afghan children to be vaccinated. According to a recent update from the WHO office in Afghanistan, children have died due to measles and pneumonia in the two western provinces of Ghor and Baghdis.

The outbreak of the disease has led the agency to issue a statement that "Measles is fully preventable by a proven safe vaccination. We call on all Afghans to vaccinate their children." Measles is a highly infectious disease that occurs through the spread of nasal and oral fluids and causes complications and deaths, even in previously healthy individuals. It is one of the leading causes of death among young children even though a safe vaccine is available.

WHO and the Afghan public health ministry had set up temporary clinics to help contain the outbreak and administer the two doses of measles vaccine as recommended by WHO. Two are recommended as about 15 per cent of vaccinated children fail to develop immunity from the first dose.

So far, more than 6200 patients were treated by the medical emergency teams, and over 3600 measles vaccinations were administered. The WHO also stated that "This outbreak confirms that the overall immunisation coverage remains low, with disparities throughout Afghanistan, particularly between rural and urban areas, secure and insecure zones."

The WHO estimated that about 30 million cases and over 700 000 deaths from measles occur annually in developing countries. Most deaths follow complications such as pneumonia, croup and diarrhoea, and are also frequently associated with malnutrition.

